Adult male.description: Baltimore Orioles have a fully black head and white wingbars instead of a black eyeline and white wing patch seen on Bullock's Orioles.

Adult female.description: The ranges of Baltimore and Bullock's overlap in the center of the continent—where they both occur, look for Baltimore's plainer, less yellowish head and less white edging on the wing coverts compared to female Bullock's Orioles.

Adult male.description: Adult male Hooded Orioles have an orange neck and head whereas adult male Bullock's Orioles have a black neck and head. Hooded Orioles also lack the black eyeline of Bullock's.

Female.description: Female/immature Hooded Orioles have more yellow on the underparts and lack the trace of an eyeline often seen on female/immature Bullock's Orioles.
Immature/female Orchard Orioles are smaller than Bullock's and more greenish-yellow than yellow-orange, especially on the belly where female/immature Bullock's tends to be grayish white.
